def: A fore-and-aft sail, bent to a gaff, and hoisted on a lowermast or on a small mast, called the trysail mast, close abaft a lowermast; -- used chiefly as a storm sail. Called also spencer. Totten.
Of or pertaining to a fish or fishes; as, piscine remains.
Successor or vicar; -- a title of the successors of Mohammedboth as temporal and spiritual rulers, now used by the sultans ofTurkey, [Writting also calif.]
Capable of being tilled; fit for the plow; arable.
Not free; held in bondage.There had always been a slave class, a class of the unfree, among theEnglish as among all German peoples. J. R. Green
Coupled without intermediate connections, as an engine and adynamo.
A large division of Articulata, embracing all those that havejointed legs. It includes Insects, Arachnida, Pychnogonida, andCrustacea.-- Ar*throp"o*dal, a.

A genus of Asiatic and American magnoliaceous trees, havingstar-shaped fruit; star anise. The fruit of Illicium anisatum is usedas a spice in India, and its oil is largely used in Europe forflavoring cordials, being almost identical with true oil of anise.
Destitute of pores; very close or compact in texture; solid.Sir T. Browne.
